entry.et: Middle English travailen, travelen to torment, labor, strive, journey, from Anglo-French travailler

def.dt: :to go on or as if on a trip or tour :journey
:to go as if by traveling :pass the news traveled fast
:associate travels with a sophisticated crowd
:to go from place to place as a sales representative or business agent
:to move or undergo transmission from one place to another goods traveling by plane
:to withstand relocation successfully a dish that travels well
:to move in a given direction or path or through a given distance the stylus travels in a groove
:to move rapidly a car that can really travel
:to take more steps while holding a basketball than the rules allow
:to journey through or over
:to follow (a course or path) as if by traveling
:to traverse (a specified distance)
:to cover (an area) as a commercial traveler
:to travel with a minimum of equipment or baggage
:the act of traveling :passage
:a journey especially to a distant or unfamiliar place :tour trip often used in plural
:an account of one's travels
:the number traveling :traffic
:movement progression the travel of satellites around the earth
:the motion of a piece of machinery
:reciprocating motion
:an agency engaged in selling and arranging transportation, accommodations, tours, and trips for travelers called also travel bureau
:a person engaged in selling and arranging transportation, accommodations, tours, or trips for travelers
:a trailer drawn especially by an automobile and equipped for use (as while traveling) as a dwelling
